WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.620 --> 00:00:10.420
&gt;&gt;Paul Stout: Thank you everyone for coming
on this Earth Day. I'm Paul Stout and it was

00:00:10.420 --> 00:00:19.750
about, I think, three or four months ago,
my lovely wife introduced me to a website.

00:00:19.750 --> 00:00:22.759
It was about, a website on Mona Caron and
I hadn't heard of her before.

00:00:22.759 --> 00:00:27.510
We got to look at the website and it was actually
pretty interesting, very intriguing. The site

00:00:27.510 --> 00:00:31.669
itself had a number of really large scale
public murals that she had done as well as

00:00:31.669 --> 00:00:35.460
a number of other types of artworks, illustration.

00:00:35.460 --> 00:00:42.989
And we thought for - it was kind of a lark
almost and a good weather report over San

00:00:42.989 --> 00:00:45.710
Francisco. We went up to the city and actually
kind of thought we'd do a Mona Caron tour

00:00:45.710 --> 00:00:51.199
because she has several different public murals,
enormous - I'm talking about - when you think

00:00:51.199 --> 00:00:56.109
of murals, you normally think of like, 'Okay,
the little thing on the side of my drugstore

00:00:56.109 --> 00:01:03.940
in town' - no, these were like 30 x 10 foot
type of murals, like huge.

00:01:03.940 --> 00:01:06.710
And so we put together a little itinerary
for ourselves, went around and there's like

00:01:06.710 --> 00:01:11.050
- it was really interesting, really thrilling
because this, the talent and the art itself

00:01:11.050 --> 00:01:15.070
is absolutely fantastic. It's just, I encourage
you all to go do this.

00:01:15.070 --> 00:01:21.000
And it was about two months ago I think or
so in January when they had the - January,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.530
February, the San Francisco Historical Society
ran a kind of a special San Francisco History

00:01:27.530 --> 00:01:33.360
Day and Mona was giving a talk there. So we
went up to see her and it was nice because

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:36.540
we're like, 'Oh, we get to put a face to this
beautiful work now'.

00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:41.140
But the interesting thing to me was that in
the talk it was - to hear a little bit, even

00:01:41.140 --> 00:01:46.380
just a little bit in that talk about her own
personal journey of discovery almost and how

00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:53.000
this public art, this idea of using, in her
case, these public murals were actually - became

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.340
really resounding points for how communities
started to come together.

00:01:57.340 --> 00:02:02.380
And this was in case, like one in particular
she's done - I'll let her get into the details

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:07.780
here but it was in the Tenderloin and these
are a lot of people who - not necessarily

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:12.990
the best part of San Francisco - have kind
of been a real center at one point and time

00:02:12.990 --> 00:02:19.530
- and people who had lived next to each other
or close to each other for maybe 20 or 30

00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:21.680
years and still didn't know each other.

00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:28.319
And yet by virtue of her coming in and starting
to do this project, now they're like a community

00:02:28.319 --> 00:02:32.939
with a vision for their future. And so the
leadership aspects of this I thought were

00:02:32.939 --> 00:02:36.999
actually very interesting, very phenomenal
especially as we start to look at how social

00:02:36.999 --> 00:02:40.359
networking - how we can play into a social
networking that is more uplifting and more

00:02:40.359 --> 00:02:44.230
building connections rather then just relying
on the connections I already have.

00:02:44.230 --> 00:02:48.820
So, without further ado, I want to let Mona
tell us her story. Thank you so much for coming

00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:50.519
today, too. Thanks.

00:02:50.519 --> 00:02:51.859
[applause]

00:02:51.859 --> 00:02:57.859
&gt;&gt;Mona Caron: Thank you so much for being
here as well.

00:02:57.859 --> 00:03:03.659
So I am going to talk to you a little bit
more about what was suggested to me by Paul

00:03:03.659 --> 00:03:10.290
that might be of interest of you today and
kind of stressing a little bit how sometimes

00:03:10.290 --> 00:03:17.760
you can use art to, to really relate to your
surroundings. And also how I use my own artwork

00:03:17.760 --> 00:03:22.920
to try and change the very surrounding around
the mural as well and not simply the wall

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:25.829
that is painted, being painted itself.

00:03:25.829 --> 00:03:29.700
I want to perhaps maybe minimize a little
bit of the statement. I definitely don't want

00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:35.040
to presume that by virtue of my little presence,
I changed an entire neighborhood. That's not,

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:36.599
not exactly what happens.

00:03:36.599 --> 00:03:41.430
In fact, the Tenderloin, as you will see,
is an incredibly rich neighborhood that actually

00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:45.569
compared to only two other neighborhoods has
a lot of social interaction. It's a

00:03:45.569 --> 00:03:51.340
place where public space is being used a lot
in very sociable ways, in ways that I think

00:03:51.340 --> 00:03:55.040
are actually pretty great and I'll show you
more of that.

00:03:55.040 --> 00:04:00.420
However there's still - anyway, I will get
more into that. I just wanted to make a clarification

00:04:00.420 --> 00:04:09.480
so I definitely do not presume to influence
the entire society to such a degree. [laughs]

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:14.959
But anyway, one scene that I chose for today
is to tie together a few of my murals. I did

00:04:14.959 --> 00:04:20.049
a whole bunch. I've been doing murals for
12 years and I have several recurring themes

00:04:20.049 --> 00:04:22.640
and one of them is that of the bird's eye
view.

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:28.069
It's like - I like to do like these kind of
views from above over things. This is sort

00:04:28.069 --> 00:04:32.259
of a cartoon that I drew for 'The Garden'
a while back that incorporates two of these

00:04:32.259 --> 00:04:36.479
aspects. One is like this view from above
and the other one is a little bit of a fantasy

00:04:36.479 --> 00:04:43.020
utopian vision that is also slightly post
apocalyptic. It's kind of a way of, you know,

00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:49.639
showing a joyful, perhaps zany through the
whole - you know, zaniness of it.

00:04:49.639 --> 00:04:55.280
Also, a little bit of a reflection of the
fact that no matter what's coming our way,

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:59.389
if there's impending disasters, I don't know
if all these things are going to happen. I

00:04:59.389 --> 00:05:06.430
insist still on trying to envision not just
our mere survival but actually a better life

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:08.740
for all of us despite all of these things.

00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:16.000
So that's kind of like the two essential points
that I try to make with these things so - so

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:21.139
I've always loved that bird's eye view thing.
So I've put myself in that vantage point quite

00:05:21.139 --> 00:05:30.120
often and it's - this is a quick charcoal
drawing I did and it's not so much about detachment

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:32.150
but about gaining perspective.

00:05:32.150 --> 00:05:36.810
Because once you kind of pull back - it's
easy when you're in the midst of life, et

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:40.110
cetera --to go like - to take things that
happen to you really personal. It's like,

00:05:40.110 --> 00:05:43.349
'Oh, why am I stuck in traffic? Why me?',
et cetera.

00:05:43.349 --> 00:05:48.629
And then like if you kind of pull back, you
see like well maybe we have a little something

00:05:48.629 --> 00:05:53.120
to do with. with how things are around us.
It's just a way of gaining perspective. It's

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:59.319
not necessarily distance or it's - it's distance
but not detachment is what I'm trying to say.

00:05:59.319 --> 00:06:07.169
It is also for me a view kind of, of innocence
from nature back into the city somehow or

00:06:07.169 --> 00:06:14.919
the civilization is kind of like a little
bit of a distance in that sense as well.

00:06:14.919 --> 00:06:21.169
Also this particular point of view that I
take is - a bird can move, right? It's dynamic.

00:06:21.169 --> 00:06:26.840
You can go low so it's low enough to see the
details and the uniqueness of each individual

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:37.539
but it's also a more - you know, it's a point
of view that allows you to see other things

00:06:37.539 --> 00:06:47.689
as well like what emerges are patterns, what
emerges are like the result, the cumulative

00:06:47.689 --> 00:06:54.360
result of our collective actions. And also
the possibility of changing things when we

00:06:54.360 --> 00:06:59.789
all get together, I guess. And it is to me
a little bit of a political vantage point

00:06:59.789 --> 00:07:04.979
because I don't do so much what I call the
"hall of the fame" murals with a lot of portraits

00:07:04.979 --> 00:07:06.520
of the people we look up to.

00:07:06.520 --> 00:07:12.080
Like here everybody is unique but you know
we're all - everybody is inhabiting the

00:07:12.080 --> 00:07:16.180
space in the same plane, like we're all in
this together and like what I'm interested

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:22.360
in looking at really is precisely that -- how
we are unique and do our own thing and how

00:07:22.360 --> 00:07:27.219
that looks like cumulatively when we do that.

00:07:27.219 --> 00:07:31.449
And so this is still the same mural - I'm
just pulling back from the tiniest to the

00:07:31.449 --> 00:07:37.389
largest so - [pause].

00:07:37.389 --> 00:07:41.699
One thing that this allows me to do because
of the sweeping views is I can make quick

00:07:41.699 --> 00:07:48.939
comparisons, comparisons across space. In
this case, the upper versus, fold under, the

00:07:48.939 --> 00:07:54.700
lower part of 24th Street in San Francisco.
So one block difference in a very different

00:07:54.700 --> 00:08:01.240
vibe and it's just a way of kind of like taking
a quick stock and a quick look at this fact.

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:09.480
And -- or it also allows me to make comparisons
across time. So this a mural - it's called

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:14.160
the Market Street Railway Mural and it's a
180 degree bird's eye view of Market Street

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:15.160
through time.

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:21.550
So those vertical strips just show a different
era. But also kind of my goal with this was

00:08:21.550 --> 00:08:32.110
kind of twofold. Like on one hand, when I
do these things, I want to use history not

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:37.060
just to make it look quaint but what I'm trying
to do actually is to use history as an argument

00:08:37.060 --> 00:08:38.620
for radical change in the future.

00:08:38.620 --> 00:08:44.730
So basically, in other words, if we compare
the way things used to look not so long ago

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:50.779
and then with the present, it's actually quite
striking and we're often, I think we often

00:08:50.779 --> 00:08:53.980
get into this, this way of thinking where
we're like, 'Well, we just need to accept

00:08:53.980 --> 00:08:57.260
the way things are', you know? 'Live in the
world you are living', like 'Face reality'

00:08:57.260 --> 00:09:01.590
and it's like you know things have changed
a lot in the past, why not again in the future?

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:07.610
And so one thing that I often do - it's like
in this case chronologically at the end, there's

00:09:07.610 --> 00:09:12.200
actually a future vision that doesn't look
radical at all because it's not that much

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:20.600
different from the present. And in fact this
is sort of the 20's but in fact a lot of things

00:09:20.600 --> 00:09:25.510
that I had in my little future vision there,
this one have already come to past.

00:09:25.510 --> 00:09:32.959
There's like bike lanes, et cetera on Market
Street, et cetera, et cetera. And one thing,

00:09:32.959 --> 00:09:39.190
another thing that I'm trying to do in these
murals is to sort of fan out a wide range

00:09:39.190 --> 00:09:46.930
of ways, legitimate ways to use public space
so often again there's like this pressure

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:50.779
where we're being told that the streets are
really for just traffic and shopping really.

00:09:50.779 --> 00:09:54.050
There's nothing else and things kind of digress
outside of that.

00:09:54.050 --> 00:09:58.600
And it's like there's many, many ways that
people have used the space and I tried to

00:09:58.600 --> 00:10:03.399
show a range of them from the celebratory
and happy to the maybe confrontational. But

00:10:03.399 --> 00:10:10.300
all of these things are part of what makes
a city a vibrant and interesting place to

00:10:10.300 --> 00:10:14.389
live. It's a place where history happens,
where politics is actually visible and not

00:10:14.389 --> 00:10:16.170
an abstract concept, you know?

00:10:16.170 --> 00:10:21.850
And so basically to remind us like - I would
love like for us to use public space more

00:10:21.850 --> 00:10:28.290
for - in convivial ways and social ways other
then just a regular old hurrying through,

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:35.930
getting to the next spot. Then these murals
- I showed you the sort of the wide view and

00:10:35.930 --> 00:10:37.120
this is a really small view.

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:42.190
You can maybe tell from the texture of the
wall how tiny that is and one of the things

00:10:42.190 --> 00:10:49.010
that I - the essence kind of, of the little
messages in my murals are actually contained

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:56.320
in the tiniest of details. And so the essence
of what really describes our humanity in our

00:10:56.320 --> 00:11:01.330
shared space and cities, et cetera is not
so much in the grand infrastructure, you know?

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:02.949
The grand building, et cetera.

00:11:02.949 --> 00:11:07.190
It's really in all the ways that people interact
with the infrastructure. So I try to show,

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:12.820
you know, like all the traces of creative
intervention onto public space, you know?

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:18.860
And like in this case quoting various poster
art and whatever I encounter here and there

00:11:18.860 --> 00:11:24.980
and also try the people, to make the people
not generic but really unique.

00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:30.630
It's just when you pull back, you can see
what they do cumulatively. And by the way

00:11:30.630 --> 00:11:38.050
all the tags in the painting are copied accurately
while all the commercial signage is slightly

00:11:38.050 --> 00:11:42.970
modified to kind of change its essence or
just like show its basic essence.

00:11:42.970 --> 00:11:45.380
[pause]

00:11:45.380 --> 00:11:46.399
Kind of get to the point.

00:11:46.399 --> 00:11:48.279
[pause]

00:11:48.279 --> 00:11:53.460
And so these are just like little references
to - this was kind of like comments on the

00:11:53.460 --> 00:12:03.030
dot com. So great. Speed up of work and stress,
et cetera. So these are the little comments

00:12:03.030 --> 00:12:08.529
but what this causes is, it causes people
to stop because they notice there's something

00:12:08.529 --> 00:12:09.720
more to see, right?

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:15.770
'Cause it's small and that's kind of exactly
my personal - like I try to reward the slowing

00:12:15.770 --> 00:12:21.690
down by hiding so many details. Why do I want
people to slow down? It's because I have like

00:12:21.690 --> 00:12:27.089
this meta purpose as I mentioned before. Like
not only do I want to advocate within the

00:12:27.089 --> 00:12:33.850
painting. You know, wouldn't it be great if
we use public space more sociably but actually

00:12:33.850 --> 00:12:40.110
try to recreate that so if you notice the
detail, you stop. Another person stops.

00:12:40.110 --> 00:12:46.759
And I - since I try to do make things very
easily - wide appeal, easily readable by everyone,

00:12:46.759 --> 00:12:52.660
and I supply a topic of conversation and at
the moment in which I have a group of people

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:58.160
going like, 'Ah, wow, that used to be really
different' or the comment on how the present

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:01.170
is being portrayed or 'What are you going
to do in the future?' or 'Ah, that's a bad

00:13:01.170 --> 00:13:05.740
idea. Do something else.' And like they started
talking to me and to each other and end up

00:13:05.740 --> 00:13:07.889
introducing themselves to each other.

00:13:07.889 --> 00:13:12.329
In that moment, I've actually achieved what
this whole thing is about. It's in that moment

00:13:12.329 --> 00:13:18.250
I've created in this little bit of space,
precisely the kind of inhabitation of public

00:13:18.250 --> 00:13:27.399
space that I'm trying to advocate. So again,
I try to work in a very wide, widely easy,

00:13:27.399 --> 00:13:34.110
you know, easy to read style like formal innovation
is - I don't really care about that stuff.

00:13:34.110 --> 00:13:38.440
But like I really just try to communicate.

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:44.370
In the future versions, this is an early one
of these, like I tried to just put little

00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:49.580
hints
that more things have changed than just infrastructures

00:13:49.580 --> 00:13:57.880
and some values and you know maybe there's
some radical societal changes instead have

00:13:57.880 --> 00:13:59.540
happened.

00:13:59.540 --> 00:14:05.380
And so from that mural on, I kept doing a
series a murals and everytime I tried to kind

00:14:05.380 --> 00:14:09.899
of push it a little further like this previous
future vision, it was a little kind of gray.

00:14:09.899 --> 00:14:13.980
It wasn't green enough. It's like where's
the green? Okay, next time, more color, more

00:14:13.980 --> 00:14:14.980
green, you know?

00:14:14.980 --> 00:14:19.760
So this is my take two, you know, on the same
thing. So the reason there's vegetables there

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:24.040
is because it's at the site of a farmer's
market and it's on the opposite side of the

00:14:24.040 --> 00:14:31.740
other one you saw. But so on one hand you
got sort of the past vision of the neighborhood.

00:14:31.740 --> 00:14:34.300
And then, on the other side, you got the future.

00:14:34.300 --> 00:14:41.860
And it's sort of better but like it came out
just maybe a little too - there's still too

00:14:41.860 --> 00:14:48.180
much pavement as - maybe too colorful, too
hippie, I don't know. It's like you never

00:14:48.180 --> 00:14:53.180
know - you try to do things and you try to
incorporate more people's ideas every time.

00:14:53.180 --> 00:14:59.509
And in this case, I invited various people
that I respect whose work about the visionings

00:14:59.509 --> 00:15:06.149
and prefigurative activities I respect to
get their input and ideas and so I came up

00:15:06.149 --> 00:15:13.240
with this and I got a lot of sort of - I keep
it zany and humorous because I don't, I'm

00:15:13.240 --> 00:15:15.860
not an engineer, et cetera.

00:15:15.860 --> 00:15:20.690
I'm just an artist. All I can do is really,
like I do my best to show things that are

00:15:20.690 --> 00:15:24.940
actually achievable with our own hands. But
sometimes I put in little jokes and stuff.

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:30.040
But, once again, if you see in the background
of the Bay Area Relaxed Transit Balloon, there's

00:15:30.040 --> 00:15:31.040
downtown.

00:15:31.040 --> 00:15:36.259
And once again it's flooded. And once again
that's what it is. I'm just - yeah, maybe

00:15:36.259 --> 00:15:42.930
things will happen. But we will still overcome
and not only survive, but get better and wiser

00:15:42.930 --> 00:15:53.000
through this. And so I – whoops.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:54.660
[pause]

00:15:54.660 --> 00:16:00.720
Okay. So here is where I'm going to - this
was sort of a brief flyover of a couple of

00:16:00.720 --> 00:16:08.740
former murals on this theme. The one that
I finished in 2010 is in the Tenderloin and

00:16:08.740 --> 00:16:16.250
it's circled there in red. It's at Jonas and
Golden Gate and I guess, Paul, you introduced

00:16:16.250 --> 00:16:18.820
the neighborhood sort of vaguely.

00:16:18.820 --> 00:16:26.310
It's, it's a very historic place. It's historic
quote "vice and entertainment district". And

00:16:26.310 --> 00:16:32.160
it's a low income neighborhood, but really,
like the societal problems are definitely

00:16:32.160 --> 00:16:38.940
are still there, it's less than it used to
be for sure. And really I've still heard it

00:16:38.940 --> 00:16:44.580
to be referred to, I believe from law enforcement,
as a containment zone which is kind of a,

00:16:44.580 --> 00:16:49.720
kind of a shocking thing. It's like a place
where certain societal problems are being

00:16:49.720 --> 00:16:53.389
concentrated and that is visible in the public
space there.

00:16:53.389 --> 00:17:00.750
But there's another side to that as I mentioned
earlier and so this is sort of a view from

00:17:00.750 --> 00:17:07.329
the mural coming up from Market Street. And
- but the Tenderloin really ought to be called

00:17:07.329 --> 00:17:12.089
a 'family neighborhood' because I was told
it is like there's a higher concentration

00:17:12.089 --> 00:17:16.049
of children in that neighborhood than almost
anywhere else in San Francisco including Noe

00:17:16.049 --> 00:17:17.049
Valley.

00:17:17.049 --> 00:17:21.490
So like there's so many people there and it's
true that you hardly see them. They're not

00:17:21.490 --> 00:17:26.850
as visible as elsewhere but that's really
at the heart of the Tenderloin. It's a very

00:17:26.850 --> 00:17:34.520
dense, incredibly rich and incredibly culturally
diverse place that has again, economically

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:38.460
poor but very rich in all of these other aspects.

00:17:38.460 --> 00:17:44.861
And so I was invited by the North of Market
Tenderloin Community Benefit District to do

00:17:44.861 --> 00:17:51.040
a mural at this particular site. They picked
the spot. The building is now vacant. Before

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:56.360
it was a garment factory. Before that it was
a porn theater, apparently the cheapest in

00:17:56.360 --> 00:18:04.480
town I'm told. But it's an old venerable building
that belongs to a Chinese Benevolent Association

00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:11.650
which means a large group of, of owners that
have it owned it forever basically.

00:18:11.650 --> 00:18:18.230
So and - but as you see this is actually not
really the way you normally see this. And

00:18:18.230 --> 00:18:23.520
the process of doing this goes as follows:
So like I went to the neighborhood. I had

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:29.950
one moderately, moderately attended meeting.
And I said, "Hi, my name is Mona. I want to

00:18:29.950 --> 00:18:34.650
- before I do any drawings, I want to learn
more about this place. So if you feel strongly

00:18:34.650 --> 00:18:39.169
about the neighborhood, if you have a story
to tell, I want to hear it. Put out the word."

00:18:39.169 --> 00:18:47.169
And boom, like response is overwhelming. And
so I preceded like many weeks of tours of

00:18:47.169 --> 00:18:51.870
the neighborhoods from very, very different
people. It was fun sometimes to get the same

00:18:51.870 --> 00:18:57.170
tour by different people and get different
versions and -- but basically just I got a

00:18:57.170 --> 00:19:03.309
sense of really the, the layers and the richness
of the place that way and again from young

00:19:03.309 --> 00:19:15.340
to old to, you know, everything from the churches
to mosques to, to like schools and sex clubs

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:19.799
[laughs] and everything.

00:19:19.799 --> 00:19:26.220
And basically - and I wanted to also mention
this one thing that's so - I did this research

00:19:26.220 --> 00:19:31.331
but I have actually lived in San Francisco
for 20 years. And I had been in the Tenderloin

00:19:31.331 --> 00:19:37.090
before this project a million times, like
I've been there many, many times. But I never

00:19:37.090 --> 00:19:42.130
want to presume to know a place because that
is only in relation to how much you reach

00:19:42.130 --> 00:19:43.520
out.

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:50.480
I think that, you know, I sort of, I feel
like whether you're a tourist or somebody

00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:56.340
who lives in a place forever, like we consciously
or sub-consciously, we always put our blinders

00:19:56.340 --> 00:20:01.059
on a little bit, you know? I actually feel
that I know way more about the places where

00:20:01.059 --> 00:20:05.789
I did the mural then I actually do on my own
block where I live which is messed up.

00:20:05.789 --> 00:20:09.010
I need to change that, you know? That is definitely
something I need to do. But there's a way

00:20:09.010 --> 00:20:15.909
in which - like there's a way of - we can,
we can screen out certain people that are

00:20:15.909 --> 00:20:20.490
not really part of our circles. And that's
how it's possible in a place like San Francisco

00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:28.210
to have so many overlapping networks of people
that actually never really interact and you

00:20:28.210 --> 00:20:31.720
know across the usual boundaries, you know?

00:20:31.720 --> 00:20:42.400
And so, let me see - and also I just want
to speak a little bit to the thing about the

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:46.200
Tenderloin. I've heard people refer to it,
'Oh but isn't it dangerous?' or something.

00:20:46.200 --> 00:20:53.560
It's definitely not. I mean, not to - things
happen but if an outsider just comes inside

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:58.450
and walks through, it's perfectly safe. And
I just think sometimes it's worth questioning

00:20:58.450 --> 00:21:01.640
what the perception of fear really comes from.

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:07.950
And you know maybe sometimes we might, we
might just be a little bit uncomfortable at

00:21:07.950 --> 00:21:14.029
the sight of poverty or you know at the sight
of otherness, culturally or racially, et cetera.

00:21:14.029 --> 00:21:19.679
And it's sometimes worth it to try and like
get past that a little bit and the rewards

00:21:19.679 --> 00:21:21.720
are many, you know?

