example, all of the families, all of these

00:34:30.620 --> 00:34:36.430
people that I met during the research process,
will be far more visible in public space if

00:34:36.430 --> 00:34:40.790
the infrastructure were more welcoming and
by the very fact itself kind of change the

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:41.790
vibe a lot.

00:34:41.790 --> 00:34:49.480
I also think it would do a lot to reduce the
degree of alienation that economically disadvantaged

00:34:49.480 --> 00:34:54.020
people feel in places like these. Like you're
really kind of punished. All you get is like

00:34:54.020 --> 00:34:57.310
sidewalks and chain link fences and no place
to sit.

00:34:57.310 --> 00:35:03.690
And a lot of people that I found in the street
are not homeless. They choose to be with people

00:35:03.690 --> 00:35:08.130
they know rather then being isolated in their
hotel Room. Like I wouldn't want to be like

00:35:08.130 --> 00:35:10.570
stuck in one room all day long, you know?

00:35:10.570 --> 00:35:17.570
And so the infrastructure kept telling me
it's so stark and there's a one way sign.

00:35:17.570 --> 00:35:20.070
By the
way, all the streets are one way in the Tenderloin.

00:35:20.070 --> 00:35:24.770
So you can imagine how cozy that is, [laughs]
you know? But look at the sign, it goes one

00:35:24.770 --> 00:35:26.580
way and that's the one way it is.

00:35:26.580 --> 00:35:31.720
Face it. This is just the way it is and I
sort of feel like there's gotta be, there's

00:35:31.720 --> 00:35:39.930
gotta be another way, you know? And so that's
what I set about to do. Just okay take two,

00:35:39.930 --> 00:35:42.510
on this
exact same street corner.

00:35:42.510 --> 00:35:50.680
What, what would it be like? What could it
be like? So what I did in this case is another

00:35:50.680 --> 00:35:57.560
utopia section. It's exactly the same place
and I did so completely collaboratively. So

00:35:57.560 --> 00:36:02.670
what I did is I - the first painting I did,
I traced that exactly. That's why they fit

00:36:02.670 --> 00:36:04.110
so perfectly in the size.

00:36:04.110 --> 00:36:09.460
It's like exactly the same basic drawing.
I traced it exactly. People recognize what

00:36:09.460 --> 00:36:12.340
I was doing and they were like, "Why are you
doing the same thing twice? You just did that."

00:36:12.340 --> 00:36:15.770
And it's like, "I know but this time different."
"What do you mean? Different how?" "Well,

00:36:15.770 --> 00:36:21.140
you tell me. You know, how could it be different?"
"I don't know."

00:36:21.140 --> 00:36:26.110
And so I had to kind of start the ball rolling
a little bit. I started by adding some verger,

00:36:26.110 --> 00:36:31.780
you know, and people got it. It's like, "Oh"
and then they started having suggestions.

00:36:31.780 --> 00:36:37.930
And I started incorporating suggestions from
the totally frivolous and fun to the really

00:36:37.930 --> 00:36:43.200
smart and thoughtful, like the whole range
of things, you know?

00:36:43.200 --> 00:36:51.840
And also crucial, crucial, crucial to this
process was to continue to include local people

00:36:51.840 --> 00:36:58.340
because what I wanted to change is an improvement
of the neighborhood without a change in population.

00:36:58.340 --> 00:37:03.250
In other words, an improvement by and for
the people who are there 'cause we all deserve

00:37:03.250 --> 00:37:04.250
that.

00:37:04.250 --> 00:37:11.540
So it's not an economic upturn. It is a DIY,
do it yourself transformation using what we've

00:37:11.540 --> 00:37:19.390
already got. Like rather then a big top down
transformation, it's something that is conceivably

00:37:19.390 --> 00:37:25.380
achievable maybe. And also I did do one thing
a little bit different this time though. So

00:37:25.380 --> 00:37:31.460
I continued putting all of the characters
and the people that I, that I met but in terms

00:37:31.460 --> 00:37:37.480
